Pre-processing a MOD16 Ea

The MOD16A2 dataset (Mu et al. 2007; Mu, Zhao, and Running 2011) is an 8-day composite product with a spatial resolution of 500 m. The algorithm is based on the Penman-Monteith equation and uses daily meteorological reanalysis data (air pressure, air temperature, humidity and radiation) in combination with remotely sensed products obtained from MODIS such as albedo, land cover, and vegetation property dynamics. This dataset provides actual evaporation (Ea) and potential evaporation (PET), which represent the summation of 8-day total water loss through ET (0.1 kg m −2 8-day −1 ), while their associated latent heat fluxes (LE and PLE, respectively) are the average total energy over a unit area per day (over the designated 8-day period) (Running et al. 2017).

Table 1 lists information about the variables provided by MOD16A2. To obtain the correct values of a variable, you must multiply the raw data by the appropriate scaling factor. This means that the product should be affected (in this case, multiplied) by this scaling factor to obtain the correct value. Note that such scaling factors are common in large datasets. The reason for making the user apply the scaling factors themselves is so that the size of the raw data file is reduced. In this case, ET values in the raw raster are saved as integers from -32767 to 32767. As those with a background in computing might recognise, 2 to the power of 16 equals 65538 (this is the length of the valid data range including the values where evaporation is not calculated), hence the value of each cell can be saved in 16 bits.

Table 1: Detailed information of the MOD16A2 product.

Datasets Meaning Units Data type Valid range Scale factor
ET_500m 8-day total ET kg m\(^{-2}\) 8d\(^{-1}\) int16 -32767 \(\sim\) 32767 0.1
LE_500m 8-day average LE J m\(^{-2}\) d\(^{-1}\) int16 -32767 \(\sim\) 32767 10000
PET_500m 8-day total PET kg m\(^{-2}\) 8d\(^{-1}\) int16 -32767 \(\sim\) 32767 0.1
PLE_500m 8-day average PLE J m\(^{-2}\) d\(^{-1}\) int16 -32767 \(\sim\) 32767 10000
ET_QC_500m Quality control - unit8 0 \(\sim\) 254 -

In addition, there are 7 fill values for non-vegetated grid-cells, where ET is not calculated (Running et al. 2017). These values are:

  1. Out of the Earth = 32767
  2. Water bodies = 32766
  3. Barren or sparsely vegetated areas = 32765
  4. Permanent snow and ice = 32764
  5. Permanent wetlands = 32763
  6. Urban or built-upareas = 32762
  7. Unclassified 32761

Objective of the task

The student should be able to read a raw MOD16A2 file (provided with this exercise) and process it to obtain ETa values.

  1. Obtain a raster file where ETa is expressed in accumulated mm over the 8-day period and all grid-cells without a measurement are stored as NAs.

  2. Export the pre-processed raster to a specific folder

Solution

Step 1: we have to read the raster ﬁle.

library(terra)
modis_path <- "C:/Users/obaezvil/Data/Part_1/MOD16A2_ET_500m_2018_361.tif"
modis_path <- "../Data/Exercise_2/Part_1/MOD16A2_ET_500m_2018_361.tif"
modis <- rast(modis_path)
plot(modis)

Step 2: now that we have read the raster, we can set the non-vegetated grid-cells (and other unclassiﬁed grid-cells) to NA values. Remember that the non-vegetated grid-cells were represented by values equal or higher than 32761.

modis[modis >= 32761] <- NA
plot(modis)

Why are the values so high? Because a scaling factor needs to be applied to the raw data to obtain the Ea values (see Table 1). Step 3: a scaling factor of 0.1 needs to be applied to the the ET_500m dataset.

modis <- modis * 0.1
plot(modis)

Always consider the order in which you perform operations to a matrix. If we had applied the scaling factor ﬁrst and then looked for cells with a value greater or equal to 32761, we would not have assigned the relevant cells values of NA.

Step 4: to export the pre-processed raster, we can use the writeRaster function.

output <- "C:/Users/obaezvil/Data/Exercise_1/Results"
writeRaster(modis, file.path(output, "MODIS_processed_2018_361.tif"),
overwrite = TRUE)

Aggregate SSEBop

The operational Simplified Surface Energy Balance (SSEBop) product (Senay et al. 2013) combines ET fractions generated from MODIS thermal imagery with reference evaporation using a thermal index approach to generate 10-day Ea estimates in milimeters. This product uses pre-defined, seasonally dynamic boundary conditions that are unique to each grid-cell for the cold/wet and hot/dry reference points. In SSEBop, eachmonth is divided into three time steps: \(i)\) the first 10 days; \(ii)\) the second 10 days; and \(iii)\) the remaining days from the 21st to the end of the month.

Objective of the task

The student should process the 10-day SSEBop to obtain monthly Ea values cropped to the extent of Rwanda for 2009–2011. The derived monthly rasters must be saved in a new folder (with information about the year and month in the file name). For this exercise, 10-day SSEBop raster files are provided (from 2008–2013). Figure 1 shows the first 16 raster files of the 10-day SSEBop data, while Figure 2 plots the shapefile where Rwanda must be subsetted.

Figure 1: First 16 SSEBop raster files provided

Figure 2: Shapefile of the Nile Basin countries

Solution

Step 1: ﬁrst, let’s load the packages that we will use.

library(terra)

Step 2: we have to store the paths that we will use: \(i)\) the one of the SSEBop ﬁles; \(ii)\) the one of the shapeﬁle; and \(iii)\) the path where the output ﬁles will be stored.

ssebop     <- "C:/Users/Data/1BSU_2/SSEBop"
shape_path <- "C:/Users/Data/1BSU_2/Countries/Nile_Basin_Countries_GAUL2014_2.shp"
output     <- "C:/Users/Data/Results/SSEBop"

Step 3: list the ﬁles in the ssebop folder.

files <- list.files(ssebop, full.names = TRUE)
head(files)

Step 4: In this step, the function grep(“2009”, basename(ﬁles)) will return the positions of the 36 ﬁles for 2009 within the list of ﬁles. That means that min(grep(“2009”, basename(ﬁles))) will return the position of the ﬁrst of the ﬁles from 2009 (in this case it will be position 37, because positions 1 to 36 are the ﬁles for 2008. Similarly, max(grep(“2011”, basename(ﬁles))) will return the position for the last ﬁle in 2011. That means ﬁles[start:end] will then return the subset of the ﬁles that are from positions 37 to 144.

# we create a vector of positions 'start:end' for all files
# that contain 2009, 2010, and 2011
start <- min(grep("200901", basename(files)))
end   <- max(grep("201112", basename(files)))
files <- files[start:end]
head(files)

nile_countries <- vect(shape_path)

Step 7: the information for Rwanda is located in the ﬁrst row of the table; therefore to subset it, we have to extract the information from the ﬁrst row.

rwanda <- nile_countries[1,]
plot(rwanda, axes = TRUE)

Step 8: let’s retrieve the years and months of each ﬁle from the ﬁle names.

# Remember that the 2 and 8 represent the position of the first
#  and last characters where the dates are stored

# Characters 6 and 7 refer to the month and character 8 refers to
#  which of the three 10-day periods in the month is considered.

dates <- substr(basename(files), 2, 7)
head(dates)
## [1] "200901" "200901" "200901" "200902" "200902" "200902"

NOTE: The function unique returns the values that are included in an object without repetition (i.e., unique values).

Step 9: SSEBop product provides three raster ﬁles per month; therefore, we will have three identical dates for each month (one per each 10-day raster). Let’s obtain the unique values in the dates object; these represent every month over which we have data available.

uniq_dates <- unique(dates)
head(uniq_dates)
## [1] "200901" "200902" "200903" "200904" "200905" "200906"

Step 10: now we have to create an iterative process that:

  1. Loops through all of the months to be analysed.
  2. Selects the ﬁles that correspond to the month.
  3. Sums the raster ﬁles corresponding to that month.
  4. Crops the raster ﬁles to the extent of Rwanda.
  5. Exports the resulting monthly raster (with a name that identiﬁes the year and month) to the output folder.
# i will take values from 1 to length(uniq_dates)
# which represent the total number of months in the data
for(i in 1:length(uniq_dates)){
  
# in the object 'pos' we will store the positions of the
# dates corresponding to the ith element in the uniq_dates object
# e.g., when i == 1, uniq_dates[i] == 200801, and pos == c(1, 2, 3)
pos <- which(dates %in% uniq.dates[i])

# now we will extract these rasters from all the files
monthly <- files[pos]
monthly <- rast(monthly)

# we use the 'crop' function to get the data only for the extent of Rwanda
monthly <- crop(monthly, rwanda, snap = "out")

# we have a stack of three rasters in the 'monthly' object
# now we can proceed to add them
monthly <- sum(monthly)

# finally, we can export the monthly raster
# for this we will create the name that each month must have
name <- paste0("SSEBop_monthly_", uniq.dates[i], ".tif")
writeRaster(monthly, file.path(output, name), overwrite = TRUE)

} # end for

Time Series Analysis

We provide a time series for daily observed streamﬂow for a catchment in Chile (presented in m 3 /s). The data are provided as a zoo object.

  1. Convert the times series to a monthly streamﬂow and plot the result.
  2. Calculate the mean streamﬂow for each season: DJF (December-January-February); MAM (March-April-May); JJA (June-July-August); and SON (September-October-November). To do this, please refer to the “extract” function in the documentation of the hydroTSM package

Solution

First we have to load the hydroTSM package.

library(hydroTSM)

Let’s set the ﬁle path.

q_path <- "C:/Users/Data/Exercise_2/Part_3/Q_observed.zoo"

Then, we have to load the ﬁle as a zoo object (it is also possible to read the ﬁle with read.table and then convert it to a zoo object).

q_daily <- read.zoo(q_path, header = FALSE)

Part A

Let’s visualise the data stored in the q_daily object.

summary(q_daily)
##      Index               q_daily       
##  Min.   :1990-01-01   Min.   : 0.0202  
##  1st Qu.:1997-04-01   1st Qu.: 1.1549  
##  Median :2004-07-01   Median : 2.3977  
##  Mean   :2004-07-01   Mean   : 3.9221  
##  3rd Qu.:2011-10-01   3rd Qu.: 5.2663  
##  Max.   :2018-12-31   Max.   :49.6193  
##                       NA's   :592
plot(q_daily)

Now, we can convert the daily time series into a monthly time series. Here, we provide the mean function to the argument FUN as we want to obtain the monthly streamﬂow in m\(³\)/s.

q_monthly <- daily2monthly(q_daily, FUN = mean, na.rm = TRUE)
summary(q_monthly)
##      Index              q_monthly       
##  Min.   :1990-01-01   Min.   : 0.06076  
##  1st Qu.:1997-03-24   1st Qu.: 1.19137  
##  Median :2004-06-16   Median : 2.48958  
##  Mean   :2004-06-16   Mean   : 3.86081  
##  3rd Qu.:2011-09-08   3rd Qu.: 5.65717  
##  Max.   :2018-12-01   Max.   :15.44473  
##                       NA's   :11

We can plot the resulting zoo object to visualise the time series.

plot(q_monthly, xlab = "Year", ylab = "Monthly mean discharge (m3/s)")

Part B

Let’s extract entries according to seasons.

q_djf <- hydroTSM::extract(q_daily, trgt = "DJF")
q_mam <- hydroTSM::extract(q_daily, trgt = "MAM")
q_jja <- hydroTSM::extract(q_daily, trgt = "JJA")
q_son <- hydroTSM::extract(q_daily, trgt = "SON")

We can plot the object q_djf to visualise the results.

plot(q_djf, type = "p")

Finally, we calculate the mean seasonal streamﬂow.

mean_djf <- mean(q_djf, na.rm = TRUE)
mean_mam <- mean(q_mam, na.rm = TRUE)
mean_jja <- mean(q_jja, na.rm = TRUE)
mean_son <- mean(q_son, na.rm = TRUE)

Finally, we can print the results of the previous step.

print(mean_djf)
## [1] 1.366668
print(mean_mam)
## [1] 2.043858
print(mean_jja)
## [1] 7.716251
print(mean_son)
## [1] 4.379506
